study_description: Targeted Gene Survey from Mouse Cecum
study_abstract: This project aims to characterize the bacterial diversity of the gut microbiome of mice deficient in toll-like receptor 5 (TLR5), in comparison with wildtype control mice.  TLR5-deficeint mice may exhibit symptoms of metabolic syndrome.  Transfer of the cecal microbiota from these mice to wildtype germfree recipients in sufficient and required to transfer the symptoms of the syndrome.  This project describes the difference in bacterial community composition and structure between a normal cecal microbiota and the cecal microbiota of the TLR5-deficient mice.  The importance of this study is that it wil help understand how a gut microbiota can confer a metabolic disease to an otherwise healthy host. Bacterial 16S ribosomal RNA sequences have been deposited in the Short Read Archive.
study_title: Altered gut microbiota in toll-like receptor 5 (TLR5) deficient mice results in metabolic syndrome

biome.definition: The environmental biome represents the major classes of ecologically similar communities of plants, animals, and other organisms. Biomes are defined based on factors such as plant structures, leaf types, plant spacing, and other factors like climate. Examples include: desert, taiga, deciduous woodland, or coral reef. EnvO terms listed under environmental biome can be found from the link: http://bioportal.bioontology.org/visualize/1069/?conceptid=ENVO%3A00000428

material.definition: The environmental material level refers to the matter that was displaced by the sample, prior to the sampling event. Environmental matter terms are generally mass nouns.
